
1-
```
<form action="submit.php" method="get" target="_self">
  <label for="name">Name:</label>
  <input type="text" id="name" name="name"><br>
  <label for="email">Email:</label>
  <input type="email" id="email" name="email"><br>
  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>

<form action="submit.php" method="post" target="_blank">
  <label for="name">Name:</label>
  <input type="text" id="name" name="name"><br>
  <label for="email">Email:</label>
  <input type="email" id="email" name="email"><br>
  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>
```

2. example of a simple canvas application in HTML5:

```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Canvas Example</title>
</head>
<body>
  <canvas id="myCanvas" width="400" height="400"></canvas>
  <script>
    var canvas = document.getElementById("myCanvas");
    var ctx = canvas.getContext("2d");
    ctx.fillStyle = "#FF0000";
    ctx.fillRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This code creates a canvas element with an id of "myCanvas" and sets its width and height to 400 pixels. It then uses JavaScript to get the canvas element and its context, and fills the canvas with red using the fillRect() method. This is just a simple example, but you can use the canvas element to create all sorts of graphics and animations in HTML5.
